# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ball-hockey-world-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/1996-ball-hockey-world-championship] The **1996 Ball Hockey World Championship** was the first ever Ball Hockey World Championship.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/1996-ball-hockey-world-championship] The championship was played in Slovakia from 11 to 15 June 1996.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] The **2011 Ball Hockey World Championship** was the ninth Ball Hockey World Championship held by ISBHF in Bratislava, Slovakia.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] 2009 champions the Czech Republic defended their title and won the championship for the third time, beating Canada in the final.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Group A contained the Czech Republic, Canada, Portugal, Germany and Finland.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Group B consisted of Slovakia, the United States, Austria, Greece and Switzerland.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Group winners advanced to the semifinals, while teams finishing second and third played a knockout match (A2 versus B3 and A3 versus B2) to determine the other two semifinalists.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] At the quarterfinal stage, the Czech Republic conceded the first goal against Greece before taking a come-from-behind 5–1 win.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] In the semifinals, held at the Ondrej Nepela Arena on 25 June 2011, the Czech Republic beat Slovakia 2–0, while Canada defeated the United States 6–5.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Slovakia won the bronze medal game against the United States, to extend their record of winning a medal in every edition of the championship.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] In the final the Czech Republic scored the only goal of the first period after 5 minutes.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] They scored twice more in the second period, either side of a Canada goal, for a 3–1 scoreline.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] A goalless final period confirmed their eighth medal in the world championship and third gold.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Further down the rankings, Finland beat Germany 4–3 for 7th place, while Austria defeated Switzerland in overtime for 9th place.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Two groups of four teams played a round-robin format.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] The top two teams in each group advanced to the semifinals.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Winners of the semifinals, France and Pakistan, each secured progress to the 2013 Ball Hockey World Championship.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2011-ball-hockey-world-championship] Pakistan defeated France in the Pool B final 6–5 in overtime.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2013-ball-hockey-world-championship] The **2013 Ball Hockey World Championship** was the tenth ball hockey world championship held by the ISBHF.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2013-ball-hockey-world-championship] The tournament took place over eight days at the Jack Byrne Arena in Torbay and the Glacier Arena in Mount Pearl, Canada, with 78 games across three divisions (men's A-Pool, men's B-Pool, and women's).
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2013-ball-hockey-world-championship] Slovakia won their second men's title, defeating the Czech Republic 2–1 in the final.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2013-ball-hockey-world-championship] Canada captured the bronze medal with a 7–3 victory over Portugal.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2013-ball-hockey-world-championship] The Canada women's national ball hockey team won the gold medal in the women's tournament, with Dawn Tulk scoring both goals in a 2–0 victory over Slovakia.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2013-ball-hockey-world-championship] In the B-Pool, Bermuda won the title over Italy in a shootout, while Israel took bronze in their first-ever World Championship appearance.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2017-ball-hockey-world-championship] The **2017 Ball Hockey World Championship** was the 12th ball hockey world championship, held in Pardubice, Czech Republic.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2017-ball-hockey-world-championship] Pardubice was announced as the host city in January 2015.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2017-ball-hockey-world-championship] It was the third time the championship was held in the Czech Republic after the 1998 and 2009 championships, which took place in Litoměřice and Plzeň, respectively.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2017-ball-hockey-world-championship] 18 men's teams took part in the tournament, which began on 1 June 2017 with the opening match of Slovakia versus India.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2017-ball-hockey-world-championship] Slovakia entered the tournament as the defending champions, having won the last two world championships.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2017-ball-hockey-world-championship] The women's competition began two days later, on 3 June.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2017-ball-hockey-world-championship] The schedule was announced on 20 January 2017.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2019-ball-hockey-world-championship] The **2019 Ball Hockey World Championship** was the 13th ball hockey world championship, and was held in Košice, Slovakia.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2019-ball-hockey-world-championship] The tournament began on 14 June 2019, with the gold medal game to be played on 22 June 2019.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2019-ball-hockey-world-championship] The Canada women's national ball hockey team defeated the United States women's national ball hockey team in the women's final to capture the gold medal, while the Czech Republic emerged with the bronze.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-ball-hockey-world-championship] The **2022 Ball Hockey World Championship** was the 14th ball hockey world championship, and was held in Laval, Canada.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-ball-hockey-world-championship] The tournament began on 21 June 2022, with the gold medal game held on 27 June 2022.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-ball-hockey-world-championship] Slovakia failed to win a medal for the first time in tournament history after losing to Greece in the quarterfinals.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-ball-hockey-world-championship] Although they went on to defeat Italy 9–0 in the 5th place play-off, national team coach Mojmír Hojer resigned from his position after the tournament.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-women-s-ball-hockey-world-championship] The **2022 Women's Ball Hockey World Championship** (French: *Championnat du monde féminin de dek hockey 2022* or *Championnat du monde féminin de hockey-balle 2022*) was the eighth women's ball hockey tournament to be held as part of the Ball Hockey World Championship.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-women-s-ball-hockey-world-championship] It was organized by the International Street and Ball Hockey Federation in collaboration with the Canadian Ball Hockey Association and was held at the Place Bell in Laval, Quebec, Canada.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-women-s-ball-hockey-world-championship] The tournament began on 21 June 2022 and medal games were played 27 June 2022.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-women-s-ball-hockey-world-championship] The Canadian women's national ball hockey team earned their sixth World Championship title after claiming a 3–2 victory over the Czech Republic in the gold medal game.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-women-s-ball-hockey-world-championship] Updated to match(es) played on 25 June 2022.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/2022-women-s-ball-hockey-world-championship] Updated to match(es) played on 27 June 2022.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] The **Ball Hockey World Championship** is a biannual ball (street) hockey competition for women's and men's national teams.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] The first championship was played in 1996 in Bratislava.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] The Ball Hockey World Championship is organized by ISBHF.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] The only medallists across the first five championships were Canada, the Czech Republic and Slovakia.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] The first team to win a medal other than those three was Italy in 2005, when they won the bronze medal.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] Held biannually, the tournament has been played in odd-numbered years since its establishment, other than 1996–1998 and 2022–2026, when it was held in even-numbered years.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] The tournament will return to odd-numbered years in 2027.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] The first women's world championships were played in 2005, located in Pittsburgh, PA.
[src:ball-hockey-world-championship/ball-hockey-world-championship] Canada have won six of the nine women's championships to date.
